idence of good cognitive competence (quick, accurate decision\u2011making and strong attention). No explicit information is provided about specific technical skills (e.g., aircraft systems, navigation, computer use), so we cannot comment on that aspect.\n**Candidate\u202fD \u2013 leadership qualities**\nThe available facts for D are:\n- *Responds to unexpected events adequately*\n- *Can concentrate very well*\n- *Solves problems extremely well*\n- *Takes responsibility seriously*\nNone of these statements directly describe leadership qualities (such as leading a crew, influencing others, or providing guidance). While \u201ctakes responsibility seriously\u201d and \u201csolves problems extremely well\u201d are positive traits that can support leadership, the data do not explicitly mention leadership ability. Therefore, we have no concrete evidence of D\u2019s leadership qualities.", "thoughts": "We need to answer using facts from candidate info. Provide info about Candidate C's technical and cognitive competence, and Candidate D's leadership qualities.\n\nFrom given info:\n\nCandidate C:\n- can make correct decisions quickly (cognitive competence)\n- difficulty communicating ideas (not technical)\n- regarded as egocentric (not competence)\n- not very willing to further his education (affects development)\n- puts concern for others above everything (maybe teamwork)\n- has excellent attention skills (cognitive competence)\nThus technical competence: not directly mentioned, but decision making quickly and excellent attention skills suggest cognitive competence. No explicit technical skill like computer or weather. So we can state we have no explicit technical skill info, but we have decision-making and attention.\n\nCandidate D:\n- responds to unexpected events adequately (maybe leadership)\n- can concentrate very well (cognitive)\n- solves problems extremely well (technical competence)\n- takes responsibility seriously (responsibility)\n- considered moody (negative)\n-