lty, which could be mitigated if the crew\u2011atmosphere note reflects effective interpersonal handling. Until we receive concrete examples of C\u2019s communication in action, C remains the leading choice.\n**Vote:** Candidate\u202fC\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_3\", \"vote\": \"Candidate C\"}", "thoughts": "We have gathered info from agents 1 and 2 via tool calls. Now we need to produce public contribution: summarize evaluation, possibly ask further questions, and vote. We have now more info: Candidate C communication difficulty but positive atmosphere; Candidate D leadership unknown; Candidate A calmness unknown; Candidate A reliability unknown; Candidate B teamwork unknown; Candidate B stress handling known; Candidate B communication issues? Not yet asked. We could ask about Candidate B's teamwork/crew cooperation. Also ask about Candidate D's leadership examples. Also maybe ask about Candidate B's communication style beyond pretentiousness. But we have already some info: B pretentious, wrong tone, but no explicit teamwork. Could ask for any positive teamwork evidence.\n\nWe need to produce public message with reasoning, ask targeted questions, and vote. Likely still Candidate C. But we should consider if new info could shift: Candidate C's communication difficulty is a concern, but positive atmosphere may mitigate. No evidence of D leadership, so D less likely. A lacks calmness and reliability evidence. B lacks teamwork. So C remains best.\n\nThus vote Candidate C.\n\nWe should ask: to Agent 2 maybe: any info about Candidate B's teamwork/crew cooperation? Also ask Agent 2 about any positive crew interaction for D? Already asked D leadership and teamwork, got none. Could ask about any examples of D leading crew? But we already asked. Could ask Agent 2 about any positive crew interaction for D. Also ask Agent 2 about any evidence of Candidate B's teamwork.\n\nLet's craft public message: summarize each candidate with strengths/weaknesses, note gaps, ask targeted questions to fill gaps, state vote."}
